[3] Brazil
Date: 9 Jul 2006 17:20:38 -0300
From: ProMED-PORT<promed@promedmail.org>
Source:Estadao [trans. Mod.LJS; edited]
<http://www.estadao.com.br/saude>

June 2006 ended with 373 autochthonous dengue cases in the capital (Sao
Paulo), about 10 times the number of cases in the same period of 2005,
close to the number found in 2002, when the country suffered the highest
number of cases. The cold weather of winter kills the mosquitoes but its
eggs remain dormant, deposited at the edges of water-holding receptacles,
capable of surviving for more than an year, hatching when the humidity and
temperature rise.
In 2006 a new phenomenon occurred: there is no epidemic in the country. The
total number of imported cases is 549, a little higher than the number of
autochthonous cases. Apart from this, for the first time serotype 3 was
found in Sao Paulo, which can cause hemorrhagic forms of the disease in
persons with previous infection by other dengue virus serotypes.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[This news is rather imprecise. There has been an increase in dengue cases
throughout Brazil in 2006. Usually the months of March and April are when
the highest number of cases occur. In the state of Sao Paulo alone, there
were 17 654 confirmed dengue cases up to June 30, a number not seen since
2002, when the state experienced the worst dengue epidemic in its history,
with more than 50 000 confirmed cases.
The capital city of Sao Paulo state, also named Sao Paulo, is not a place
badly hit by dengue. The 390 cases confirmed this year (official figure) as
of June 30 is unusual, but far from an epidemic, as the city has around 10
million inhabitants (the metropolitan area has around 20 million). Numbers
from the rest of the country are not available for 2006, but fragmentary
data show that dengue epidemics are occurring in different parts of the
country.
Dengue virus, serotype 3 has been identified in the state of Sao Paulo
since 2002; the fact that it was found in the city is not remarkable. -
Mod.LJS]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
