[4] Bangladesh
Date: 11 Jul 2006 03:42:45 -0400 (EDT)
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: People's Daily Online, Beijng, China, 8 Jul 2006 [edited]
<http://english.people.com.cn/200607/08/eng20060708_281310.html>

At least one person died and over 100 others have been infected as dengue
fever resurfaced in the Bangladeshi capital Dhaka during the last 3 days, a
health ministry control room said on Saturday.
An emergency doctor in the Holy Family Hospital confirmed the death of a
dengue patient and said everyday they are receiving many new patients of
dengue in the hospital.
Dr ASM Raihan in the Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujib Medical University on
Saturday said the dengue outbreak this time was a bit earlier due to the
scattered rains. He said the _Aedes_ mosquito, responsible for carrying the
virus, might grow due to the scattered rains.
"The number of patients is increasing every day in the university
hospital," Dr Raihan said. He said the number of dengue patients
comparatively was more than that of the previous year and these patients
are getting admitted to different hospitals and clinics.
Raihan could not give the exact number of patients, but said everyday many
patients are falling ill with the fever and being admitted to different
hospitals and clinics.
In Bangladesh during the monsoon, the deadly dengue surfaces almost every
year and kills scores of people annually.
--
