[5] India
Date: 11 Jul 2006 03:42:45 -0400 (EDT)
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source:Kolkata Newsline, New Delhi, India, 11 Jul 2006 [edited]
<http://cities.expressindia.com/fullstory.php?newsid=192248>

The official count in the number of dengue infection cases has risen to 15,
as per the record books of the Kolkata Municipal Corporation (KMC).
The civic health department today added to its list the name of a resident
of ward 119 in Behala who was brought to the Balananda Brahmachari Hospital
with high fever on 29 Jun 2006. Subsequent blood tests confirmed that he
was suffering from dengue.
The health department of KMC has suggested that this infection be
considered an "imported case". "He had arrived in the city on 25 Jun 2006
after a prolonged stay in Bihar. The incubation period of the dengue virus
(the period between the virus' entry into the human body and the detection
of symptoms) is usually 8-10 days.
"Our probe suggests that he had to be admitted to hospital in less than a
week's time. This prompts us to believe that he brought the infection from
Bihar," said Dr DD Chattopadhyay, chief municipal health officer.
Dey said the KMC health officials have been urged to take the "dengue
awareness and control programme" in right earnest. "Some officials don't
understand the importance of the exercise. We want a motivated staff," said
Dey. "The state health department told us that it shall make all necessary
arrangements in 4 city hospitals -- Calcutta Medical College and Hospital,
National Medical College and Hospital, RG Kar and NRS Hospital -- for free
dengue tests," Dey added.
--
