[7] Venezuela
Date: 11 Jul 2006
From: Alfonso J. Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Epidemiological Alert, 26th Epidemiological Week, Ministry of
Health, Venezuela, 25 Jun - 1 Jul 2006, MSDS, Venezuela [trans Mod.AJR; edited]
<http://www.msds.gov.ve/msds/Boletines/Alertas/2006/Boletin26_2006.zip>

During this epidemiological week 1021 dengue fever were diagnosed, 64 of
which were hemorrhagic dengue fever (6.3 percent), and the classical dengue
fever/hemorrhagic dengue fever ratio was 15:1. The cumulative case toll for
this year is 21 834 cases, 5.3 percent of which are hemorrhagic dengue
fever (1161 cases), and the classic dengue fever/hemorrhagic dengue fever
ratio is 18:1. The cumulative morbidity rate is 82.2 per 100 000
inhabitants. Circulating serotypes are 1, 2, 3, and 4. The cumulative case
toll for this period has a 44 percent increase compared to that for 2005
(15 162 cases). During this week, no deaths caused by dengue fever had been
reported.
A 3.9 percent reduction in the number of cases compared to last week was
recorded. The age groups most affected are 5 to 9 years old (23.8 percent),
followed by 15 to 24 years old (22.5 percent), 10 to 14 years old (19.8
percent), 25 to 44 years old (15.6 percent), and 1 to 4 years old (10.8
percent).
States reporting the highest case numbers are as follows: Zulia (312),
Amazonas (113), Lara (78), Tachira (74), Barinas (69), Merida (57), Miranda
(52), and Trujillo (42), comprising 78.1 percent of all dengue fever cases
reported in Venezuela.
